Metropolitan Avenue, north side, opposite Seventieth Avenue (known also as Ursula Place and Herrick Auerue). This set of 3 views shows the home of Jeronus Vanderveer. John and Walter Vcrgderveer were the owners in 19E3 while one Weeden was the occupant. Michael Vanderveer who settled in Newtown in 1810 was born in Flathush in 1777. Pe rarried Martba Vandervoort of Newtoxn. His son Henry Suvdam was born in 1812 in the old koose that stood across the road fror his latter residence, whick was on the w:st side of Trotting Corrse Lane just south of Metropolitan Avenue. TEe son, Nenry Suydam, married Sarah J. (Burroumhs) Rapelje in 1807. George W. Vandorveer was born in the oli family homestead in Newtown in 1842. He rarried in 1848 hary Whitson of that place. Charles Boerur: Vandcrveer (1796. 1879) owned a thirty-six acre farm at Middle Village. His son 'eronus purchased about 1871 a sixty acre one at the same place. After his fathrs death he, Jeronus, acoufred bia fatkerw farr.. Othr ovners of this house ere E. Randall, 188O7;H. Needen, 1873; and J. Vanderveer, in 1896. Views 2 and 3 are viewed
east and west resectively.
1922
Views 2a:3: Uctober 1923.
Eugene L. Armhroster Collection
